    "id": "swift",
    "term": "SWIFT",
    "category": "payments",
    "definition": "the Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication—a global messaging network that banks use to securely exchange international transfer instructions.",
    "content": "<h3 style=\"font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--primary-color); margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 12px; font-family: serif; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 6px;\">1. Overview</h3><p style=\"line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px; color: var(--text-dark); font-size: 14.5px;\">To understand <strong>SWIFT</strong>, it helps to start with the absolute basics of how banking works. A bank is a secure place where people and businesses keep their money. Instead of carrying large amounts of cash or hiding it at home, you store it in a bank account. The bank keeps track of exactly how much money is yours using a digital record called a ledger. When you buy something, pay a bill, or receive your salary, money must move from one person's account to another. Payments and clearing systems are the electronic roads and traffic rules that allow these funds to travel safely between different banks.</p><p style=\"line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 20px; color: var(--text-dark); font-size: 14.5px;\">In this system, <strong>SWIFT</strong> is defined as <em>the Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication—a global messaging network that banks use to securely exchange international transfer instructions.</em> It serves as a vital component of daily banking operations, ensuring that transactions are recorded correctly, assets are safeguarded, and credit is evaluated fairly.</p><h3 style=\"font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--primary-color); margin-top: 24px; margin-bottom: 12px; font-family: serif; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 6px;\">2. How It Works: Step-by-Step Tutorial</h3><p style=\"line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px; color: var(--text-dark); font-size: 14px;\">Here is a step-by-step breakdown explaining how this concept functions in practice:</p><ol style=\"margin-left: 20px; margin-bottom: 24px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; padding-left: 0; list-style-type: decimal;\"><li style=\"line-height: 1.6; padding-left: 6px; color: var(--text-dark); font-size: 13.5px;\"><strong>Messaging:</strong> A bank formats a standard SWIFT message (such as an MT103 wire instruction).</li><li style=\"line-height: 1.6; padding-left: 6px; color: var(--text-dark); font-size: 13.5px;\"><strong>Transmission:</strong> The message is transmitted securely to the destination bank overseas.</li><li style=\"line-height: 1.6; padding-left: 6px; color: var(--text-dark); font-size: 13.5px;\"><strong>Settlement:</strong> The receiving bank reads the message and coordinates fund clearing through correspondent accounts.</li></ol><h3 style=\"font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--primary-color); margin-top: 24px; margin-bottom: 12px; font-family: serif; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 6px;\">3. Practical Impact: Why This Matters to You</h3><p style=\"line-height: 1.7; color: var(--text-dark); font-size: 14.5px; margin-bottom: 20px;\">SWIFT does not move actual cash; it acts like a secure international chat system for banks. When you send money abroad, SWIFT carries the instructions so foreign banks know to credit the recipient.</p>",
    "related": [
      "wire-transfer",
      "correspondent-banking"
    ],
    "diagram": null
